Further Graph Customizations

Muhammad Hilmi Abdul Majid

Introduction

In the previous units, we have explored visuals and graphs that we can use to display data, depending on the type of data we have and what we want to show to the audience. When plotting a graph, we have used several techniques to make it more aesthetically better. This include using colors, modifying axes, adding title and subtitle, and more. In this unit, we will further discuss the customizations we can do when plotting graphs.

This unit is based mainly from Chapter 11 of Modern Data Visualization with R by Robert Kabacoff. As usual, we first load the ggplot2 and dplyr packages.

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

Axes and Scales

Axes refer to the x and y-axes that forms the coordinate of points or elements in the canvas. Using ggplot2, we can modify the axes using the scale functions.

Quantitative axes

For quantitative axes, we typically use scale_x_continuous() or scale_y_continous() functions. The former is for the x-axis, and the later is for the y-axis. Here are some options we can include when using the functions:

  • breaks: A vector for the positions of ticks on the axis.

  • limits: A vector with two elements used to specify the min and max value for the axis.

Below is the default scatterplot without using the scale functions

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) +
  geom_point()

And here are the same graph after changing the x and y-axes scales. Note that the command seq(from=1, to=7, by=0.5) forms a vector for the sequence of numbers from 1 to 7 where the difference between two consecutive values is 0.5

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  
  # Set the x-axis ticks to 1, 1.5, 2, 2.5, ..., 7
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(from=1, to=7, by=0.5)) +
  
  # Set the y-axis to be between 10 and 50
  scale_y_continuous(limits=c(10,50))

If some cases, we may want to specify the type of data for the x and y-axes. We can use the scales package which provide useful functions for formatting the axis labels. These functions are used as the argument for labels inside of the scale functions. Some of the useful ones are:

  • label_currency(): Used to convert the format to currency.

  • label_percent(): Used to convert the format to percentage. Note that the scale value 1 is equivalent to 100%.

  • label_comma(): Used to convert the format to using comma, i.e. 100,000 instead of 100000.

# Generate random data
set.seed(1234)
df <- data.frame(xaxis = rnorm(50, 100000, 50000),
                 yaxis = runif(50, 0, 1),
                 pointsize = rnorm(50, 1000, 1000))

# Load scales package
library(scales)

ggplot(data=df, mapping=aes(x=xaxis, y=yaxis, size=pointsize)) +
  geom_point(color="cornflowerblue", alpha=0.5) +
  
  # Use comma for the x-axis
  scale_x_continuous(labels=label_comma()) +
  
  # Use percentage for the y-axis
  # Note that 1 is equivalent to 100%
  scale_y_continuous(labels=label_percent()) +
  
  # Use currency (RM) for the size legend label
  scale_size(labels=label_currency(prefix="RM"))

Categorical axes

For categorical axes, we can use scale_x_discrete() or scale_y_discrete() functions. Some of the options when using these functions are:

  • limits: A vector of character/string/text used to specify order of categorical names.

  • labels: A vector of character/string/text used to rename the labels on the axis.

Here is the default plot output:

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=class)) +
  geom_bar(fill="cornflowerblue")

And here is the plot output after changing the labels position using limits and names using labels. Note that the \n used in the labels represent line breaks.

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=class)) +
  geom_bar(fill="cornflowerblue") +
  
  # Change the order of classes and change the label names
  scale_x_discrete(limits = c("pickup", "suv", "minivan", 
                             "midsize", "compact", "subcompact", 
                             "2seater"),
                   labels = c("Pickup\nTruck", 
                              "Sport Utility\nVehicle", 
                              "Minivan", "Mid-size", "Compact", 
                              "Subcompact", "2-Seater"))

Date axes

For axes with dates, we can use scale_x_date() or scale_y_date() functions. The options for customization include:

  • date_breaks: A text or string that gives the distance between two axis ticks. For example, we can use "2 weeks" or "10 years".

  • date_labels: A text or string that gives the format for the date labels.

For the date formatting, the table below gives the specifications for the symbols and the output examples.

Date formats and symbols
Symbols Meaning Example Output
%d Day in number 01, 05, 31
%a Weekday (abbreviated) Mon, Tue
%A Weekday (unabbreviated) Monday, Tuesday
%m Month in number 01, 05, 12
%b Month (abbreviated) Jan, Feb
%B Month (unabbreviated) January, February
%y Year in two digits 00, 07, 25
%Y Year in four digits 2000, 2007, 2025 
ggplot(data=economics, mapping=aes(x = date, y = unemploy)) +
  geom_line(color="firebrick") +
  
  # Set tick marks to every 5 years
  # Use 'abbreviated month'-'two digit year' (eg Jan-70)
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "5 years",
               date_labels = "%b-%y")

Colors

Colors of points, rectangles, lines, and event scales can be changed in R and ggplot2. Using colors can make the graphs more pleasing and easier to read.

Choosing color manually

To choose a color manually, we can use color="colorname" as the argument for the geom functions. In some geom functions, we can also use fill="colorname" option for filling bars, rectangles, the inside of point characters, and so on.

To display all available color names, you can run the colors() function. You can also use hexcode when specifying color, for example color="#121212".

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) +
  
  # Use the #ab8adb hexcode color
  geom_point(color="#ab8adb")

If you have groups or categorical variables, you can also specify the colors in vector forms.

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=class)) +
  
  # Use the colors for each respective category
  geom_bar(fill=c("cornflowerblue", "firebrick", "darkgreen", "turquoise",
                  "seagreen1", "royalblue", "salmon"))

And if you have data with levels, you can use scale_color_manual() and scale_fill_manual() functions to change the colors associated with the levels

ggplot(data=diamonds, mapping=aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  geom_bar() +
  
  # Use the colors for the levels for fill
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("darkred", "steelblue", 
                               "darkgreen", "gold",
                               "brown", "purple", 
                               "grey", "khaki4"))

Color palettes

Specifying each individual colors can be a difficult and challenging task. To simplify this process, we can use the available color palettes available in R.

One of the common color palettes used is the ColorBrewer palettes. It is available in the RColorBrewer package and is included in the ggplot2 package.

ColorBrewer color palettes

To use the ColorBrewer palettes, use the scale_color_brewer() or scale_fill_brewer() functions. We can also add the argument direction=-1 to reverse the color direction in the palette.

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  geom_bar() +
  
  # Use ColorBrewer (spectral) palette for fill
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Spectral")

Another popular color palette is the viridis color palette. It is also available in the viridis package but also included in the ggplot2 package.

To use this color palette, we can use scale_color_viridis_c() and scale_fill_viridis_c() for continuous scales, or scale_color_viridis_d() and scale_fill_viridis_d() for discrete (or categorical) scales.

ggplot(data=diamonds, mapping=aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  geom_bar() + 
  
  # Use viridis color palette for fill
  scale_fill_viridis_d()

You can change to similar color palettes to viridis using the mentioned functions together with the option argument.

Color scale alternatives to viridis
ggplot(data=diamonds, mapping=aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  geom_bar() + 
  
  # Use mako color palette for fill
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option="mako")

Points and Lines

Points

By default, the point character or shape used is the filled circle. The point chape used when can be changed using the shape argument in the geom_point() function. Below are the shapes corresponding to the numerical value associated with the shape argument. Note that shapes 21 to 25 can be filled with colors.

Values for point shapes

Additionally, the size of the points can be modified using size argument in the geom_point() function.

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) +
  
  # Use cicle with fill (shape=21), change color, fill and size
  geom_point(shape=21,
             color="grey50",
             fill="salmon",
             size=2)

Lines

The regular solid line is used by default when no specification is used. To change the line type in ggplot2, we can use the linetype argument in the geom_line() function or other similar functions. Below are corresponding line types and their numerical values.

Line types

The line width can also be modified using the linewidth argument.

ggplot(data=economics, mapping=aes(x = date, y = unemploy)) +
  
  # Use dotted line type and 1.5 line width
  geom_line(linetype=3,
            linewidth=1.5)

Legends

Legends are automatically added when variables are mapped to the color, fill, linetype, shape, size, or alpha in the aes() mapping. We can modify the position of the legend using the theme() function, and change the legend title using the labs() function.

By default, legends are placed on the right side of the graph. But we can change the legend position by using the legend.position argument inside the theme() function.

Legend position options
Position Location
"top" Top of the graph
"bottom" Bottom of the graph
"right" Right side of the graph
"left" Left side of the graph
c(x, y) At the specified x-y position. The x and y values must be between 0 and 1. c(0,0) represents the bottom-left position and c(1,1) represents the top-right position.
"none" Hide the legend

As for the legend title, we can modify this using the labs() function. If the legend is mapped to the color, we use color argument in the function. Similarly, if the legend is mapped to fill, we use fill argument.

The alignment of the legend title can also be modified using legend.title.align argument in the theme() function with 0 being left-aligned, 0.5 being center-aligned, and 1 being right-aligned. The title position relative to the legend can also be changed using the legend.title.position argument.

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color=class)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(color="Car class") +
  theme_minimal() +
  
  theme(legend.position = "top",        # Set legend at top
        legend.title.position = "top",  # Set legend title at top of legend
        legend.title.align = 0.5)       # Set legend title to be center-aligned

Axis, Legend, and Plot Labels

The labs() function can be used to change the modify the axis, legend, and plot labels. Here are the argument inside of the function and its use.

Arguments and options for labs()
Argument/Option Use
title Title of the plot
subtitle Subtitle of the plot
caption Caption of the plot (at the bottom right by default)
x x-axis label
y y-axis label
color Legend title for color
fill Legend title for fill
size Legend title for size 
ggplot(data=mpg,
       mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy,
                   color=class,
                   shape=factor(year))) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = .5) +
  labs(title = "Mileage by engine displacement",         # Change title
       subtitle = "Data from 1999 and 2008",             # Change subtitle
       caption = "Source: EPA (http://fueleconomy.gov)", # Change caption
       x = "Engine displacement (litres)",               # Change x-axis label
       y = "Highway miles per gallon",                   # Change x-axis label
       color = "Car Class",                              # Change color legend title
       shape = "Year") +                                 # Change shape legend title
  theme_minimal()

Annotations

Annotations are used when you draw additional text or lines on the graph to highlight certain things. They can be great if used carefully, but may cause the end result to be too cluttered and busy if not used properly

Adding texts to label values

Text can be added in ggplot2 to label values using the geom_text() and geom_label() functions with the later having a background rectangle behind the text, but the two are functionally the same. Adding labels to points on the graph can be useful if we want to identify them.

The geom_text() and geom_label() require the x and y position in the aes() mapping for the position of the text. Additionally, the label argument is also required for the text that will be added at the specified position.

ggplot(data=mtcars, mapping=aes(x=wt, y=mpg)) +
  geom_point() +
  
  # Add labels at the x-y position
  geom_text(label = row.names(mtcars)) +
  
  theme_minimal()

As we can see in the plot above, the added labels causes the plot to be too busy and hard to read. We can overcome this by using the ggrepel package and the geom_text_repel() and geom_label_repel() functions included in the package. These functions forces texts and labels not to overlap each other.

Additionally, we can reduce the size of the text using the size argument. You can also use the color and alpha arguments or options for further customization.

library(ggrepel)

ggplot(data=mtcars, mapping=aes(x=wt, y=mpg)) +
  geom_point() +
  
  # Add labels at the x-y position that do not overlap
  geom_text_repel(label=row.names(mtcars),
                  size=3,
                  color="steelblue") +
  
  theme_minimal()

Adding texts to describe plot

Another use case for adding text on a graph is to add additional information and description regarding the plot. We can use the annotate() function to do this with the geom or the first argument being "text". The function also requires x, y, and label arguments for the x-y position and the text.

By default, the text will be center-aligned. We can change the alignment using hjust argument (0=left-aligned, 0.5=center-aligned, 1=right-aligned). The alignment will use the specified x-y position as the reference point. Additionally, the vjust argument can be used to change the vertical position of the text with respect to the x-y position (0=above, 0.5=centered, 1=below).

sample_text <- "Cars with more weight tend\nto have lower miles per gallon"

ggplot(data=mtcars, mapping=aes(x=wt, y=mpg)) +
  geom_point(color="red") +
  geom_text_repel(label=row.names(mtcars),
                  size=3,
                  color="steelblue") +
  
  # Add 'sample_text' text at the x-y position
  # Make it right-aligned and above the x-y position
  annotate(geom="text", label=sample_text,
           x=5, y=30,
           hjust=1, vjust=0) +
  
  theme_minimal()

Adding vertical or horizontal lines

In some cases, we might want to add horizontal or vertical lines. For example, if we want to compare the data that we plot to a given reference value, we can draw horizontal or vertical line for the reference value.

We can add horizontal and vertical lines using geom_hline() and geom_vline(), respectively. We can also add other options such as the line type, line width, and colors, similar to the ones used in geom_line().

mean_hwy <- mean(mpg$hwy)
ggplot(data=mpg, 
       mapping=aes(x=cty, y=hwy, color=drv)) +
  geom_point(size=3) +
  
  # Add horizontal line at mean_hwy
  geom_hline(yintercept=mean_hwy,
             color="darkred",
             linetype = "dashed") +
  
  # Add text above horizontal line
  annotate(geom="text", 
           x=9, 
           y=mean_hwy + 1.5, 
           label="Mean",
           color="darkred") +
  
  labs(title = "Mileage by drive type",
       x = "City miles per gallon",
       y = "Highway miles per gallon",
       color = "Drive")

Highlighting selected group

Sometimes, we want to focus the audience’s attention to a single group. We can use the gghighlight() function in the gghighlight package for this.

In the example below, we want to highlight the midsize class. The color specified in geom_point() is used just for the selected midsize class only.

# install.packages("gghighlight")
library(gghighlight)

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=cty, y=hwy)) +
  geom_point(color="red",
             size=2) +
  
  # Highlight the midsize class
  gghighlight(class=="midsize")

Similarly for the plot below.

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x = class)) +
  geom_bar(fill="red") +
  
  # Highlight the midsize class
  gghighlight(class=="midsize")

Combining Graphs

In some cases, you may want to combine several graphs into a single plot or image. You can do this using the patchwork package which expands ggplot2 for combining multiple plots.

After installing and loading the package, we first need to save the individual plot as an object. Then, we can use mathematical operators to combine them. For example, using the + or | operators between two ggplot objects will make the two plots side-by-side on the same row.

# install.packages("patchwork")
library(patchwork)

# Save first plot as an object
p1 <- ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=cty, y=hwy)) + geom_point()

# Save second plot as an object
p2 <- ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) + geom_point()

# Combine first and second plot side-by-side
p1+p2

Using / operator on the other hand signifies the start of the next row.

# Save first plot as an object
p1 <- ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=cty, y=hwy)) + geom_point()

# Save second plot as an object
p2 <- ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) + geom_point()

# Combine first and second plot with first plot on top of second plot
p1/p2

We can also use multiple operators to combine multiple graphs into one plot. Additionally, after combining the plots, we can use the & operator which applies a function to all graphs. In the example below, we apply both theme_minimal() and gghighlight() function for all three graphs. We also used plot_annotation() function from the patchwork package to add title to the entire plot.

# install.packages("patchwork")
library(patchwork)

# Save three different plots
p1 <- ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=cty, y=hwy)) +
  geom_point(color="red")
p2 <- ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) +
  geom_point(color="red")
p3 <- ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x = class)) +
  geom_bar(fill="red")

# Combine the three plots
(p1 | p2) / p3 &
  
  # Apply theme_minimal() to every plot
  theme_minimal() & 
  
  # Highlight midsize class in every plot
  gghighlight(class=="midsize") &
  
  # Add title to the combined plot
  plot_annotation(title="Combining graphs and highlighting midsize cars")

Conclusion

In this unit, we have explored various ways we can use to further customize graphs produced using ggplot2. At the end of the day, the use case scenario for these additional customization depends on what you want to achieve. For example, highlighting a single group out of the rest may be useful if you want to focus on the group, or adding text on the graph can be useful if you want to add information. However, over-customization can also be a problem and cause the plot to be too busy.
